FRONTEND AGENT – MASTER RULES & UX SPEC
CodeArena: The Neural Combat Network
The frontend must look and feel like a premium dark SaaS dashboard crossed with a neon hacker‑gamer arena (similar to the reference screenshots), while staying performant and readable.

1. Tech Stack & Architecture (Non‑negotiable)
Framework: React 18+ (or React 19 if already configured) with TypeScript.
​

Bundler: Vite.
​

Routing: React Router (App Router already in project).
​

Styling: TailwindCSS with custom design tokens.
​

State:

React Context for auth.
​

Zustand OR React Query for app/server state where appropriate.
​

API: Axios client with interceptors, using the shared API_BASE_URL and ENDPOINTS config.
​

Editor: @monaco-editor/react for code editing.
​

Real‑time: socket.io-client for WebSocket‑based features.
​

Use the existing project layout: src/components, src/pages, src/contexts, src/services, src/config, src/styles, etc., do not invent a new structure.
​

2. Visual Identity & Design System
2.1 Core Aesthetic
Base background: true black or near‑black (#000000 / #02010A) with soft radial gradients in corners (neon “blooms”).

Accent palette:

Electric cyan: #00F5FF

Hot pink: #FF10F0

Neon purple: #B01EFF

Radioactive green: #39FF14

Typography:

Display headings: a futuristic sans (e.g., Orbitron/Space Grotesk) for big titles.

Body text: clean, neutral sans (Inter, system stack).

Effects:

Glassmorphism: translucent cards with backdrop-blur and subtle borders.

Neon glows: sparse but impactful box-shadow and outer glows for CTAs, key stats, and hero elements.

Gradients: angled neon gradients for primary buttons and hero backgrounds (e.g., cyan → pink).

Tailwind tokens:

Extend tailwind.config.js with colors like arena-bg, arena-card, arena-cyan, arena-pink, arena-purple, arena-green and use them consistently instead of hexes in components.
​

2.2 Layout Principles
Hero pages (landing, marketing):

2‑column layout: text on left, live/animated preview on right (editor, dashboard, or battle).

Centered max width (~1200–1440px) with generous padding (top ~96px, sides ~24–40px).

App dashboard:

Desktop: left sidebar with icons/labels, main content panel, optional right “activity” panel.

Mobile: bottom or slide‑in navigation; collapsible sidebar.

Spacing:

Use a clear spacing scale (4/8/12/16/24/32/40/48px).

No cramped UI; breathing room around cards and sections.

3. Global UX Rules
Always show clear primary CTA above the fold (e.g., “Start Battle”, “Get Started”, “See How It Works”).

Every page must have:

A visible page title + short supporting subtitle.

A consistent navbar and/or sidebar for navigation.

Proper loading states (skeletons/spinners) and error messaging.

Never leave a screen in a “blank” state:

Use empty states with one sentence explaining what’s missing and a CTA (e.g., “No battles yet. Start your first match.”).

Use optimistic but honest microcopy:

Buttons: “Start Battling”, “Join Queue”, “Run Code”, “Submit & Fight”.

Alerts: “Something broke, but your code is safe. Try again.” instead of generic “Error.”

Accessibility:

High contrast text on dark backgrounds.

Focus outlines must be clearly visible.

All interactive elements must be keyboard accessible (Enter/Space triggers).

4. Pages & Flows (End‑to‑End UX)
4.1 Landing Page (/)
Goal: Sell the concept like a real product marketing site (think CoCreate + “Master coding through real‑time battles”). It should feel like a startup homepage, not a dev demo.

Sections (in order):

Hero Section

Left:

Eyebrow label: “CodeArena Presents” or “THE NEURAL COMBAT NETWORK”.

H1: short, punchy value prop (e.g., “Master coding through real‑time battles.”).

Subtext: 2 lines explaining “algorithms that fight, evolve, and can die permanently.”

Primary CTA: gradient neon button “Start Battling” (if unauthenticated → signup/login, if authenticated → dashboard).

Secondary CTA: subtle outline button “See how it works” that scrolls to overview or opens a short explainer.

Social proof row: “10K+ matches played”, “Loved by competitive coders”, or placeholder stats.

Right:

A “mock app preview” card:

Top: fake code editor card (Monaco style) with syntax highlighting and a small header (e.g., “Solution.java”).

Bottom: stat cards showing “Current rank”, “Win rate”, “Terminal feed” similar to your reference.

Smooth entrance animation (Framer Motion: slide‑up + fade with slight scale).

How It Works

3–4 horizontal cards:

“1. Queue for a match”

“2. Code in real‑time”

“3. Win, evolve, and climb leaderboards”

Each card: icon, title, 2 lines of copy, subtle hover lift + glow.

Feature Grid (Bento style)

Highlight: real‑time battles, Evolution Wars, living algorithms (traits/permadeath), replays/roasts/God Mode.
​

Use a Masonry/Bento layout with different card heights and background accents.

Social Proof / For Whom

Rows like: “For ICPC competitors”, “For interview prep grinders”, “For DevOps nerds building insane infra”.

Final CTA

Hero‑like band with short value statement and single strong CTA “Join the Arena”.

Behaviour:

If user is logged in, navbar should show “Dashboard” instead of “Get Started”.

Use Framer Motion for section fade‑ins and simple parallax on scroll, but avoid over‑animating every element.

4.2 Auth Pages (/login, /signup)
Goal: Fast, clean, minimal friction, still aligned with neon theme.

Layout:

Split screen:

Left: compact card with form.

Right: illustration / blur‑gradient background with a single sentence like “Algorithms are battling right now. Join them.”

Form UX:

Inputs: large, full width, proper labels, placeholder text, and error messages.

Buttons: one primary action per page (“Log In”, “Create account”).

Links: “Forgot password?”, “Already have an account? Log in” with clear navigation.

Copy:

Login: “Welcome back to the Arena.”

Signup: “Create your pilot profile.” (username, email, password, confirmation).

Validation:

Show inline field errors (red text below input).

Disable submit button while submitting; show a small spinner indicator.

4.3 Dashboard (/dashboard)
Goal: Feel like a professional SaaS workspace with a gamer skin; central hub for everything.

Layout:

Left sidebar (always visible on desktop):

Logo + app name.

Sections:

Home / Overview

Battles

Algorithms

Problems

Leaderboard

Guild (later)

Settings

Use icons (lucide‑react) plus labels.
​

Main content area:

Top row:

Greeting (“Welcome back, {username}”).

Quick stats chips: current ELO, win rate, current streak, active algorithm count.

Body:

Left: “Next Action” cards:

“Quick Match” card with a big button.

“Daily Challenge” card with streak indicator.

Right: Activity feed:

Recent battles (result, opponent, problem, time).

Recent algorithm events (evolved, learned trait, died/permadeath).

Components:

Use cards with consistent padding, border, and glow on hover.

Animate counters for ELO/XP changes (react‑countup).
​

Use toasts (react‑hot‑toast) for small success/info messages when actions complete.
​

4.4 Problems List (/problems)
Goal: Professional, filterable table like a SaaS “Issues/Tasks” page.

Layout:

Top bar:

Page title: “Problems”.

Search input (by name/tags).

Filters: dropdowns for difficulty, tags, status (solved/unsolved).

Content:

Responsive table with columns:

Name

Difficulty (colored pill)

Acceptance rate / success rate

Estimated time (e.g., 15 min battle | 10 min solo)

Actions (“Solve”, maybe “Practice solo”).

Alternating row background; on hover, row slightly lifts and highlights.

Behaviour:

Clicking a row or “Solve” opens ProblemDetail (coding interface) and optionally offers:

“Start solo practice” or “Use in 1v1 battle” depending on context.

4.5 Problem Detail / Coding Arena (/problem/:id)
This is the heart of the app; it must feel like a cockpit, not a generic editor.
​

Layout:

Top:

Breadcrumb: “Problems / {Problem title}”.

Right: “Watch Replay” (if there’s a recorded session) and maybe status badges.
​

Main split:

Left panel (40–50% width, resizable via drag bar):

Problem title + difficulty pill.

Scrollable problem description (markdown rendered).

Tabs or segmented control:

Description

Examples

Constraints

Test cases (visible ones only).

Right panel:

Monaco editor with language selector, theming aligned with neon (custom dark theme).
​

Action bar:

“Run Code” (primary ghost button).

“Submit” (primary solid gradient button).

Small indicator: “REC ●” when God Mode/session recording is active.
​

Bottom pane:

Tabs: “Console”, “Test Results”, “Performance”.

Show per‑test results: pass/fail, input snippet, expected vs actual.
​

States:

Loading: skeletons for both panels.

Running: disable buttons, show “Running tests…” with spinner.

Submit success:

Immediate toast + inline banner “Solution accepted – preparing your roast…”.
​

After a delay, show “Roast My Code” modal.
​

Submit fail:

Highlight failing tests, show human‑friendly error summary.

Viral features (hooked here):

Roast My Code modal:

Animated text reveal, context‑aware roast and share button (share text + copy link).
​

God Mode Replay:

“Watch Replay” button opens rrweb player modal with playback controls.
​

4.6 Battles List & Match Details (/battles, /battles/:id)
Goal: Make battles feel like match history in ranked games.

Battles list:

Filters: mode (Gladiator/Evolution/etc.), result (win/loss), timeframe.

Columns:

Opponent, problem, result, score, time, mode, “View”.

