Battle detail:

Header:

“You vs {opponent}” with result pill (Win/Loss/Draw).

Summary grid: ELO change, score, duration, problem name.

Body:

Tabs:

“Overview” (scores, charts).

“Code Comparison” (split view showing both final solutions).

“Timeline” (events: runs, submits, tests).

“Replay” (hooks into God Mode and/or highlight if available).
​

Actions:

“Rematch”, “Copy challenge link”, “Share results”.

4.7 Leaderboards (/leaderboard)
Tabs:

Global, Friends, Guild, Algorithms.

Table or cards with:

Rank, username, avatar, ELO, wins/losses, streak.

Mini CTA: “Challenge” for each row to start a direct challenge vs that player.

4.8 Profile / Settings (/profile, /settings)
Show:

Avatar, username, bio, country, preferred language.

Stats summary: battles, streaks, traits unlocked.

Settings:

Account info, theme toggles (sound on/off, particle intensity, etc.).

5. Component System & Behaviour
5.1 Core Reusable Components
AppLayout: root layout with:

Background (OLED gradient, subtle animations).

Navbar and optionally sidebar, depending on route.
​

Navbar:

Left: logo + “CodeArena”.

Center: top‑level nav (Product, Learn, etc. on marketing; Dashboard, Battles, Problems on app).

Right: auth CTA (Log in/Sign up) or user avatar dropdown if authenticated.
​

SidebarNav:

Icon + label items, highlight active route.

Compact collapsed mode with just icons on small widths.

PrimaryButton, SecondaryButton, GhostButton:

Encapsulate gradient styles and hover/focus states so they are consistent.

Card:

Reusable glassmorphism container with shadow and border.

StatBadge:

Small pill showing stat label and value (e.g., “ELO 1420”, “Win Rate 68%”).

Never write raw button/div for important actions; use these abstractions.

5.2 Animations Guidelines
Use Framer Motion for:

Page transitions (fade/slide in).

Hero elements (slight entrance).

Hover effects on cards and buttons.
​

GSAP/Three/Vanta/Particles:

Reserve for landing and maybe high‑impact backgrounds (animated beams, waves), not for every screen.
​

Performance:

Avoid heavy 3D/particle animations on core app pages that must stay snappy (editor, battles).

Provide a “reduced motion / low FX” toggle in settings and respect OS prefers-reduced-motion where possible.

6. Data Flow & Integration
All API interactions must go through the apiClient and services layer (authService, challengesAPI, etc.) instead of calling fetch or axios directly in components.
​

Authentication:

Use existing AuthContext for user/token state; do not reinvent auth.
​

Protected routes must use the existing ProtectedRoute wrapper.
​

Real‑time:

Wrap WebSocket logic in custom hooks like useBattleSocket/useMatchmakingSocket instead of using socket.io-client directly everywhere.
​

7. States, Errors, and Feedback
For every async operation (API call, WebSocket join, match creation):

Show loading:

Button: spinner + “Loading…” text, disabled state.

Screen: skeletons or centered spinners where appropriate.
​

Handle errors:

Small toast with human message (“We couldn’t fetch your battles. Retrying…”).

In place fallback UI if critical (“Couldn’t load problems. [Retry]”).

Show success feedback:

Toasts for major events (login, match won, evolution complete).

Confetti (react‑confetti) only for big milestones (first win, major rank up), not for every action.
​

8. Coding Standards (Frontend‑Specific)
Use TypeScript strictly; no any for new code unless truly necessary.
​

Component files:

One primary component per file with explicit props interface.

Keep components under ~200 lines; factor out subcomponents as needed.

Hooks:

Prefix with use* and keep them pure and reusable.

Avoid:

Inline business logic in JSX; compute outside the render or in hooks.

Duplicating layout logic across pages; use layout components.

9. Frontend Non‑Goals (To Avoid Confusion)
Do not implement DevOps or infrastructure concerns in frontend (no Docker/K8s stuff here).

Do not build an entire no‑limits 3D game; visuals must support UX, not overshadow it.

Do not change global routing/architecture away from the documented structure without explicit instruction.
​

